For many, commemorating #ArmisticeDay today will be a lonelier affair than usual.

Join Chief Yeoman Warder Pete McGowran and Yeoman Gaoler Rob Fuller at the #TowerOfLondon for a virtual 2 minute silence, as the clock at the nearby Waterloo Block strikes 11am.

node.text:
Long before we started texting under the table at parties, Georgian ladies were using a much simpler handheld device to send messages across the room: their fans! 

Whether you want to introduce yourself, flirt a bit, or just get that annoying courtier to leave you alone, here’s your instructor Lucy Worsley with some of the key phrases you’ll need in order to learn the secret language of the fan. Remember to pay close attention — there’ll be a vocab test at the end 🤓

node.text:
From the 12th century until the 1600s, new Kings and Queens traditionally processed through the city from the #TowerOfLondon ahead of their coronation at @westminsterabbeylondon, as a great way to assert their power and show themselves off in front of their public.
 
Now it’s your turn! Walk in the steps of royalty along the coronation route from the Tower to the Abbey this Bank Holiday weekend 👑 Find out more and book tickets via the links in our bio.

node.text:
We’ve got exciting news. We’re ready to start reopening the palaces! 🥳

On Thursday 18 June our beautiful gardens at Hampton Court Palace and Hillsborough Castle will reopen to the public. We’ve assembled a top team from across the palaces to run you through the new measures we’ve put in place to ensure we can offer everyone a safe and enjoyable visit.

Meanwhile, our work preparing our other outdoor spaces for reopening continues, with indoor spaces at the palaces to follow in line with the latest advice. We look forward to sharing more updates with you soon.

Follow the link in our bio to find out more about visiting and book your tickets.

.

.
If you love the Tower and believe in what we do, we’d be so grateful if you’d consider supporting our work by becoming a Member. Find out more via the link in our bio.

node.text: The conservation team are investigating the magnificent ceiling of the Wolsey Closet at #HamptonCourtPalace. For many years, it was thought to be made of a material called leather maché, but it was revealed that this is not the case. The exact date and origin of the ceiling are also a mystery. This detective work will let them choose the best conservation methods in order to conserve this glorious craftwork for another 500 years. 🕵️‍♀️

node.title: Conservation of a Tudor ceiling | Beyond Palace Doors

node.text: How do you make an 18th century chandelier? 🕯️ Part of recent restoration work at #KensingtonPalace included hanging new golden chandeliers in the State Apartments. It has taken four years to complete the chandelier project, in which the items were researched, designed and crafted from scratch, with only one visual record and a few descriptions to go on. The carved and gilded chandeliers now hang in the King’s Drawing Room at Kensington for the first time in nearly two centuries.

Here is Queen Victoria’s gold and enamel pocket watch 🕔 It was an 11th birthday gift from her mother and is inscribed with a message from the Duchess to her daughter. Curatorial Assistant Aisha Tahir tells us what the watch reveals about Victoria’s childhood. 
The pocket watch is on loan to #KensingtonPalace from the Harewood House Trust and the 8th Earl of Harewood. 
See the watch on display at Kensington for #Victoria200: http://bit.ly/Victoria200

node.text:
Experience #MindBehindTheMyth at #KewPalace in a more personal way, with our new series of evening tours 🌙

In a small group you’ll be guided through our groundbreaking exhibition, uncovering the true story of George III and how attitudes to mental health have changed over the last 200 years — and how they haven’t. 

And you’ll also get to explore secret parts of the palace kept shut during the day, including the attics and the original Tudor undercroft.

Tours run on Tuesday evenings until 10 August. Find out more and book via the link in our bio ☝️

On 16 July 1557, Anne of Cleves died at Chelsea Manor, aged 42.

Today remembered primarily as the 4th wife of Henry VIII, who famously declared “I like her not” and had their marriage annulled after just 6 months, Anne has been treated harshly by popular history.

Follow the link in our bio to read a blog from Chief Curator Tracy Borman, separating the fact from the fiction to tell us the true story of Anne’s life.

node.text:
On 12 July 1543, Henry VIII married his sixth wife Katherine Parr in the Holy Day Closet at #HamptonCourtPalace. This intimate space next to the Chapel Royal survives to this day, and is now known as the Lady Chapel 💍

Like Henry, Katherine was also a widower — although unlike Henry she’d been married only twice before (and both previous husbands had died of natural causes!) 

They remained together until Henry’s death 4 years later, and during that time Katherine became a loving stepmother to his 3 children. As the first English queen to write and publish her own books, crucially Katherine helped shape the young Princess Elizabeth’s own ideas of female leadership.

node.text:
On 6 July 1535, Thomas More was executed on Tower Hill.

As a member of Henry VIII’s council and later Chancellor of England, More had been one of the most powerful men in the country, as well as a celebrated humanist philosopher and author. But when Henry wanted to annul his marriage to Katherine of Aragon and break from the Catholic Church, More refused to acknowledge him as the Supreme Head of the Church, and resigned.

For his disloyalty, More was imprisoned in the #TowerOfLondon on 17 April 1534, and, over a year later, executed on charges of treason. It is said that his last words were “I die the King’s good servant, and God’s first”.

To this day More’s remains are buried in the Tower’s Chapel of St Peter ad Vincula.

📷 @royalcollectiontrust

node.text:
Happy 700th birthday to Joan of the Tower! 🎈

Born on 5 July 1321 here at the #TowerOfLondon (which explains her *awesome* name), Joan was the youngest daughter of Edward II and Isabella of France. Joan became Queen of Scotland at just 7 years old when she was married to to David II of Scotland, then aged 4 😬

Later in life Joan found herself back at the Tower, this time visiting her husband in prison following his capture by the English after the Battle of Neville’s Cross in 1346. After David’s eventual release in 1357, Joan decided to remain in England, and she died at Hertford Castle in 1362.
